issue.title: Mesh is invisible, but I can see it as a collision. DAE model

content.raw:
I am using a custom mesh that I made in Blender.  It worked great in Gazebo 7, but isn't working since upgrading to Gazebo 9.  I can see the .stl collisions if I set the Model view to see collisions (and the quadcopter crashes into them if I force it to), but the .dae is invisible in the viewer.  But I don't see an error related to it while running gazebo --verbose.

Here is the world file (just in case):

```
#!html
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<sdf version="1.4">
  <world name="default">
<!--<include>
      <uri>model://ground_plane</uri>
    </include>-->
    <include>
      <uri>model://sun</uri>
    </include>
    <light type="directional" name="my_light" cast_shadows="true">
      <origin pose="0 0 30 0 0 0"/>
      <diffuse rgba=".9 .9 .9 1"/>
      <specular rgba=".1 .1 .1 1"/>
      <attenuation range="20"/>
      <direction xyz="0 0 -1"/>
    </light>
    <model name="my_mesh">
      <pose>0 0 0  0 0 0</pose>
      <static>true</static>
      <link name="body">
	<collision name="collision">
	  <geometry>
		  <mesh><uri>file:///usr/share/gazebo-7/worlds/uofu_labeless_aligned_truenorth.stl</uri></mesh>
	  </geometry>
        </collision>
	<visual name="visual">
	  <geometry>
		  <mesh>
			  <uri>file:///usr/share/gazebo-7/worlds/uofu_labeless_aligned_truenorth.dae</uri>
		  	  <scale>1.0 1.0 1.0</scale>
		  </mesh>
  	  </geometry>
	</visual>
      </link>
    </model>
    <model name="iris">
      <include>
        <uri>model://iris_with_standoffs_demo_9002</uri>
      </include>
      <pose>56 -25 8 0 0 0</pose>
    </model>
  </world>
</sdf>


```

content.raw: I see, maybe it's different from the original issue. The SDF file looksok. If your mesh is public, it would be helpful to look at it. There could be something in the collada mesh which was parsed one way in Gazebo 7 and another way on Gazebo 9.

content.raw: Pull request #2616 seems relevant, page 223 of the [COLLADA spec ](https://www.khronos.org/files/collada_spec_1_4.pdf) tells how to use the  `<transparency>` tag.
content.html: Pull request #2616 seems relevant, page 223 of the COLLADA spec tells how to use the <transparency> tag.

issue.title: Mesh is invisible, but I can see it as a collision. DAE model

content.raw:
I think the ColladaLoader did not implement the following logic from the spec:

> If <transparency> does not exist then it has no effect on the equation’s result. This is equivalent
to a factor that is 1.0:
 transparency = <float> 1.0 <float> 

currently if the `transparency` is missing we default to 0, and the calculations resulted in a transparent mesh.
content.html:
I think the ColladaLoader did not implement the following logic from the spec:

If <transparency> does not exist then it has no effect on the equation’s result. This is equivalent to a factor that is 1.0: transparency = <float> 1.0 <float>

currently if the transparency is missing we default to 0, and the calculations resulted in a transparent mesh.

content.raw: I am having issues with the mesh being invisible in Gazebo 9, too. In Gazebo 7 the meshes worked just fine, but for any meshes now where the material is just a diffuse color I set up in Blender, in Gazebo 9 the mesh will be invisible. If I have a texture as a image will make the image visible again, but then I had to bake all the texture from my old meshes.
content.html: I am having issues with the mesh being invisible in Gazebo 9, too. In Gazebo 7 the meshes worked just fine, but for any meshes now where the material is just a diffuse color I set up in Blender, in Gazebo 9 the mesh will be invisible. If I have a texture as a image will make the image visible again, but then I had to bake all the texture from my old meshes.
